  "prompt": "How many views I have to have on YouTube to earn money?",
  "response": "The number of views you need on YouTube to start earning money isn't fixed, as it depends on several factors. Here's what you need to know:\n\n1. **Join the YouTube Partner Program (YPP):**\n   - To monetize your videos, you must first apply for the **YouTube Partner Program (YPP)**.\n   - As of October 2023, the eligibility requirements for YPP are:\n     - **1,000 subscribers**\n     - **4,000 valid public watch hours in the past 12 months** **or** **10 million valid public Shorts views in the last 90 days**.\n\n2. **Views vs. Revenue:**\n   - YouTube pays based on **ad revenue**, which depends on factors like:\n     - Ad type (e.g., skippable ads, non-skippable ads).\n     - Viewer demographics (e.g., country, age).\n     - Advertiser demand.\n   - On average, creators earn **$0.01 to $0.03 per view**, but this varies widely. For example:\n     - 1,000,000 views might generate **$1,000 to $5,000**, depending on the above factors.\n\n3. **Focus on Engagement:**\n   - Monetization isn't just about views. **Engagement** (likes, comments, shares) and **watch time** are critical for growing your channel and maximizing earnings.\n\nIn summary, while there\u2019s no specific \"view count\" to start earning, you need **1,000 subscribers** and **4,000 watch hours or 10 million Shorts views** to qualify for monetization. After that, your earnings will depend on your content, audience, and ad performance.",
